Interesting… I posted the same question a few days ago

Dual-pressure pneumatic actuation Pneumatics
Looking for a rule and sanity check here. I THINK this should work, but could use some extra eyes on it. I was thinking of having a mechanism that can be actuated with different pressures. As such, what i would seem to need is a solenoid with 2 inputs and 1 output. I would need this without the 2 inputs being connected to each other, else the pressures would equalize and render the whole thing useless, and without either bleeding to atmosphere. So this is what i came up with. 2 solenoids i…

For yours, I assume the “S” devices are solenoid valves… what are the 120 and 60?

The first thing you’re missing is check valves (i.e. valves that only allow pressure in one direction) so the pressure from the 2 branches isn’t feeding backwards into the other branch. You also need some way of tying the whole thing to your pressure dump valve legally.

R813(a) and R814 (page 107) are going to make this very difficult to do legally.

R813: You have to prove there is no pressure in the system

R814: two outputs cannot be plumbed together, depending on how you read that rule there are two outputs that could become considered together.

What you can do is plumb up two separate actuators. There are also some other mechanical tricks you can do to reduce grip pressure, the biggest and easiest one just being the surface area of your gripper. You can also reduce forces the griper exerts by having mechanical hardstops bottom out and bear some of the force from the cylinder.

We did this in 2018. The component you need is called a “shuttle valve”. It takes two inputs and directs the higher pressure one to the output.

mcmaster.com

McMaster-Carr

McMaster-Carr is the complete source for your plant with over 595,000 products. 98% of products ordered ship from stock and deliver same or next day.

So

  • run one solenoid valve on 60 psi feed into one input of the shuttle valve
  • run a second solenoid valve on 20 psi (or whatever) and feed it into the other input
  • feed the output of the shuttle valve into your cylinder.
  • depending on which solenoids you activate, you can now supply your cylinder with 60 psi, 20 psi, or 0 (vent).

JCharlton:

The outputs from multiple solenoid valves must not be plumbed together.

We QA’d this rule when we used a shuttle valve in 2018, and our implementation was ruled legal. The point of R814 is to prevent teams from ganging several solenoid valves in parallel to bypass the flowrate limitations. The shuttle valve only allows flow from one solenoid valve at a time.

You might run afoul of R814: *Don’t connect solenoid outputs together. The outputs from multiple solenoid valves must not be plumbed togethe

The diagram I posted uses the other port of the “high pressure” solenoid valve to retract the cylinder (the left-most blue line running from V1 to the “front” of the cylinder). You could also use the “low pressure” solenoid valve to retract the cylinder if you prefer (currently that part is shown capped-off). Assuming you only want one pressure on retract, there’s no need for a third valve or a spring return cylinder.

If you want to both extend and retract the cylinder at different pressures, you’ll need a second shuttle valve yeah (and maybe a third solenoid valve?)
